On receipt of a report regarding a missing child by a law enforcement agency, the law enforcement agency shall immediately determine if:
the missing child has not been the subject of a prior missing persons report;
the missing child suffers from a mental or physical handicap or illness;
the disappearance of the missing child is of a suspicious or dangerous nature;
the person filing the report of a missing child has reason to believe that the missing child may have been abducted;
the missing child has ever previously been the subject of a child abuse report filed with the State or local law enforcement agency; or
the missing child is under 17 years of age.

Upon conclusion by the law enforcement agency that any one of the conditions specified in subsection (a) of this section exists, the law enforcement agency shall immediately:
enter all necessary and available information into the Maryland Interagency Law Enforcement System (MILES) and the National Crime Information Center (NCIC) computer networks;
institute appropriate intensive search procedures, including the coordination of volunteer search teams;
notify the National Center for Missing and Exploited Children and forward to the State Clearinghouse for Missing Children a copy of the missing persons report involving the missing child;
notify the appropriate local department and, to the extent possible, obtain any information that may assist in the locating of the missing child; and
enlist the aid of the Department of State Police, when appropriate, in locating the missing child.
